observations.recommendation:
We recommended that Municipal Mayor to instruct the Municipal Accountant to:
a. Require the Municipal Accountant to maintain individual subsidiary ledger card per taxpayer or per barangay per year to ensure that receivables and collections for each given year as well as adjustments, if any, are posted in the respective SLs to provide the account details and balances by year, and to facilitate verification and monitoring of the said accounts’ balances and actual RPT and SET collections for each given year; 
b. Instruct the Municipal Accountant and Municipal Treasurer to reconcile their records and determine the cause of the deficiencies noted between their records, prepare reconciliation, and make the necessary adjustments, and submit to the Audit Team the results and the actions taken; 
c. Require the Municipal Treasurer to exhaust all efforts and devise strategies to collect all delinquent real property taxes and encourage the taxpayer to pay their dues on time. Conduct verification on those outstanding balance to determine the accuracy of the receivables and its collectivity; and 
d. Consider the application of the legal remedies including the assistance of the Provincial Government for the auction of some delinquent real properties.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor require the: 
a. Municipal Engineer to submit justifications and explanations regarding the overestimated Contract Cost and noted delays in the implementation of the projects; 
b. Municipal Engineer to submit documents to support the Time Extension Order for further evaluation of the Audit Team; 
c. Municipal Engineer to strictly monitor the completion of infrastructure projects as specified in the Contract Agreement and ensure that Time Extension Order are duly approved by the Local Chief Executive; and 
d. Municipal Accountant ensures that payments for infrastructure projects are supported with documents justifying delayed completion pursuant to 2016 Revised IRR of RA No. 9184, otherwise, liquidated damages be deducted from claims of contractors.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor instruct the Municipal Health Officer (MHO) to:
a. provide the Municipal Accountant with the inventory reports, attach all Requisition Issue Slips (RIS) and Property Transfer Records (PTRs) of all donations in-kind (vaccines, ancillary supplies, etc.) received by the Balayan RHU related to its COVID-19 Vaccination Program; 
b. include in their monitoring the receipts and ancillary supplies and provide the Municipal Accountant of pertinent information and records for the appropriate recognition thereof; 
c. Municipal Accountant to record in the books the inventory as of year-end of all donations in-kind with available cost information; and 
d. Municipal Accountant in coordination with the MHO to obtain from donors the necessary information as to the unit cost and quantities of vaccines or any other ancillary supplies received by the Municipality in the future.

We recommended the Municipal Mayor to:
a. Enjoin the Municipal Accountant and Municipal GSO to identify the causes of the discrepancies between the PPELCs and RPCPPE, and adjust their records accordingly. In addition, create a separate Inventory Committee for one-time cleansing of PPE required under COA Circular No. 2020-006 and approve the Physical Inventory Plan necessary to conduct the physical inventory; 
b. Instruct the duly created Inventory Committee, the Municipal General Services Office and Municipal Accounting Office to adopt the general guidelines, procedural guidelines, and reconciliation of inventory count per RPCPPE with property and accounting records required under COA Circular No. 2020-006 in the conduct of inventory taking for one-time cleansing of PPE; 
c. Cause the conduct of an investigation to determine the last known location/office of non-existing/missing PPE items, the persons accountable therefor, the circumstances of the loss, and the persons responsible for such loss. Issue demand letters to the accountable personnel to produce the properties or pay the depreciated replacement cost thereof, as provided in Section 7.0 of COA Circular No. 2020-006; and 
d. Request authority from the COA for the derecognition in the books of accounts of those non-existing/missing PPE items for which accountability could not be established, in accordance with Section 8.0 of COA Circular No. 2020-006.

a) We recommended that the Municipal Mayor require the Municipal Accountant to coordinate with the Municipal General Services Officer to determine the details of the beginning balances of the Property, Plant and Equipment (PPE) from their oldest available records for proper accountability and adjustment of accounts;
b) We recommended that the Municipal Mayor require the General Services Office and Accounting Offices to make periodic reconciliation of the PPE accounts to arrive at reconciled balances to present a more reliable financial statements;
c) We recommended that the Municipal Mayor instruct the Municipal Accountant to recognize in the municipality’s books the appropriate asset account arising from Trust Fund for the current and prior periods;
d) We recommended that the Municipal Mayor require the GSO to have an updated list of unserviceable items and prepare all the necessary inspection documents/reports to act on the unserviceable properties to be disposed within the reasonable time to prevent further deterioration of the PPE.
